1) What is a Thread Pool in Java?
-->A Thread Pool is a collection of pre-created worker threads used to execute multiple tasks efficiently without creating new threads every time.
  Advantages:
      Better performance
      Reuses existing threads
      Reduces thread creation overhead
      Improves resource management

    A thread pool in Java is a collection of pre-initialized, reusable worker threads managed by the java.util.concurrent framework.
    Instead of creating a new thread for every task—which is a costly operation for the CPU and memory—tasks are submitted to a shared
    queue and executed by the available threads in the pool.
    
    How It Works:
    Initialization: A specific number of threads are created and kept in an idle state.
    
    Task Submission: When a new task (Runnable or Callable) is submitted, the pool manager checks for an available thread.
    
    Execution:
      If a thread is free, it immediately picks up and executes the task.
      If all threads are busy, the task is placed in an internal blocking queue to wait.
    
    Reuse: Once a thread finishes its task, it does not "die." It returns to the pool to wait for the next task from the queue.




2) What is the Executor Framework? How to implement thread creation, management, and scheduling by using thread pools?

The Executor Framework is a framework in Java used for:

thread creation
thread management
task scheduling

It simplifies multithreading using thread pools.

Example:
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;

class Test implements Runnable {

    public void run() {

        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName());
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ExecutorService ex =
                Executors.newFixedThreadPool(3);

        ex.execute(new Test());
        ex.execute(new Test());
        ex.execute(new Test());

        ex.shutdown();
    }
}



3) What is the difference between Executor, ExecutorService, and Executors class?
-->
| Executor           | ExecutorService               | Executors                |
| ------------------ | ----------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Parent interface   | Child interface of Executor   | Utility class            |
| Executes tasks     | Executes + manages lifecycle  | Creates thread pools     |
| Contains execute() | Contains submit(), shutdown() | Contains factory methods |
